The goal here is to prove that for any $a, b$ in $R$, if $a \in I \cap J$ and $b \in I \cap J$, then $a + b \in I \cap J$.

To prove this, we need to show that if $a$ and $b$ are in both $I$ and $J$, then their sum is also in both $I$ and $J$.

Since $I$ is an ideal, it is closed under addition. So if $a \in I$ and $b \in I$, then $a + b \in I$.

Similarly, since $J$ is an ideal, if $a \in J$ and $b \in J$, then $a + b \in J$.

Therefore, $a + b \in I \cap J$.

So the proof should proceed by taking arbitrary $a, b$ satisfying the hypotheses and then proving $a + b \in I \cap J$.

